Yale face data¶

  • The database consists of 2410 images of 38 individuals.
In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.io import loadmat
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import warnings
import time
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
import packages_and_functions as func

Data Structure¶

  • allFaces.mat provides keys and values of Yale faces.
  • We need to create labels and get characteristics of faces by calling its keys ("faces" and "nfaces")
In [ ]:
faces_data = loadmat("allFaces.mat")
X = faces_data["faces"].T
y = []
for i, x in enumerate(faces_data["nfaces"][0]):
    y += [i+1] * x
group = np.unique(y)

Part1. Original Data¶

Data Preprocessing¶

  • Split the data into training and testing part
  • Standardization

Note: we assume that the test data is invisible, so we standardize test data with mean and std from train data.

In [ ]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state = 410878048)

# Standardize the test data by means and std from train data
X_var_mean = np.array(np.mean(X_train, axis = 0)).reshape(1, -1)
X_var_std = np.array(np.std(X_train, axis = 0)).reshape(1, -1)
X_test = (X_test - X_var_mean)/ X_var_std

# Standardize the train data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)

Grid Search¶

Again, in order to get the maximized result, we in advance perform grid search.

Due to the need of a great deal of time handling larger data, we decide to reduce the sets of parameter we would try.

The final result shows, in training data, logistic regression model would get most excellent score under the set of parameter {'max_iter': 100, 'n_jobs': -1, 'penalty': 'l2', 'solver': 'lbfgs'}.

In [ ]:
# Logistics Regression parameters
params = {
    'penalty': ['l2'],
    'solver': ['lbfgs'],
    'max_iter': [100], "n_jobs" : [-1]
}
print("Logistic Regression")
log_params = func.gridSearch("LogisticReg", params, X_train, y_train)

# SVM parameters
params = {
    'C': [0.1],           
    'kernel': ['linear'],    
    'gamma': ['scale'],       
    'degree': [2],                
    'tol': [1e-5],        
    'max_iter': [100]
}
print("SVM")
svm_params = func.gridSearch("SVM", params, X_train, y_train)

# Neural Network parameters
# Define a dictionary of hyperparameters to search over
params = {
    'hidden_layer_sizes': [(50,), (100,100)],
    'activation': ['relu'],
    'solver': [ 'adam'],
    'alpha': [ 0.01],
    'max_iter': [100],
    'tol': [1e-5]
}
print("Neural Network")
nn_params = func.gridSearch("NeuralNetwork", params, X_train, y_train)

Classification Result¶

  • Time of training of 3 models is about five minutes (320 sec)

datas = [X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test]

CM_SVM, _ = func.classificationChoice("SVM", group, *datas, paras_dict = svm_params)

end_time = time.time()

  • heatmaps of confusion matrix

    At this time, test data includes all of subjects, so we do not need to use stratify in train_test_split.

    Because of larger test data, more misclassified cases occurs, but most of them are correctly classified.

In [ ]:
model = ["Logistic Regression", "SVM", "Neural Network"]
for i, CM in enumerate([CM_LogReg, CM_SVM, CM_NeuralNetwork]):
    plt.figure(figsize=(11, 15))
    # Create a heatmap of the confusion matrix using seaborn
    plt.imshow(CM, cmap='Greens')

    # Add text to each cell of the heatmap
    for j in range(CM.shape[0]):
        for k in range(CM.shape[1]):
            text = plt.text(k, j, f'{CM[j, k]}', ha='center', va='center', color='Orange', fontsize=15)

    # Add labels for the x and y axes
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for {model[i]} Model')
    plt.show()

  • Table of index

    When the index is below 60%, we color the cells in purple.

    From the viewpoint of precision and recall, Logistic regression model achieve the best performance with high averaged recall (94.7%) and high averaged precision (94.5%) and does not produce any purple cells in the meanwhile.

    These index become more stable than that of AT&T data because of larger test data.

    Neural network model has lower precision in subject 29 (55%), which means nearly half of prediction of subject 29 are wrong. This model performs worse in subject 29 and so on.

Part2. PCA Data¶

Data Preprocessing¶

  • With dimensionality reduction, we retrieve more important variables from original data. Then, we check if the classification would be improved

  • At the first experiment, retaining 80% variance leads to a terrible classification. Therefore, we turn to retain 70 variables which account for more than 95% variance of original data

  • Train test split -> Standization -> PCA

In [ ]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state = 410878048)
# Standardize the test data by means and std from train data
X_var_mean = np.array(np.mean(X_train, axis = 0)).reshape(1, -1)
X_var_std = np.array(np.std(X_train, axis = 0)).reshape(1, -1)
X_test_std = (X_test - X_var_mean)/ X_var_std

# Standardize the train data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_std = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)

pca = PCA()
pca.fit(X_train_std)
# decide the retained number of PCs
cumulative_variances = np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_)
percentage = [x/X.shape[1] * 100 for x in cumulative_variances]
number_retained = list(np.array(percentage) > 95).count(False) + 1
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_[:number_retained]
tick_of_pc = [x for x in range(1, len(explained_variance)+1)]

X_train = pca.transform(X_train_std)[:, :number_retained]
X_test = pca.transform(X_test_std)[:, :number_retained]

# show pca result
## plot bar chart
color1 = "blue"
plt.bar(tick_of_pc, explained_variance, color=color1, alpha=0.5)
plt.xlabel('The Number of Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Explained Variance', color=color1)
plt.tick_params(axis='y', color=color1)
## create secondary y-axis
ax3 = plt.twinx()
## plot cumulative percentage line chart
ax3.plot(tick_of_pc, percentage[:number_retained], color='purple', marker='o', alpha = 0.5)
ax3.set_ylabel('Cumulative Percentage (%)', color='purple')
ax3.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='purple')

Grid Search¶

The final result shows, in training data, Neural network model would get the most excellent score under the set of parameter {'activation': 'logistic', 'alpha': 0.0001, 'hidden_layer_sizes': (100,), 'max_iter': 1000, 'solver': 'adam', 'tol': 1e-05}.

params = {
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2', 'elasticnet'],
    'C': [0.1, 1, 10],
    'solver': ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'sag'],

log_params = func.gridSearch("LogisticReg", params, X_train, y_train)

# SVM parameters

    'C': [0.1, 1, 10],

    'gamma': ['scale', 'auto'],

    'tol': [1e-5],

# Define a dictionary of hyperparameters to search over

    'hidden_layer_sizes': [(50,), (100,), (100,100)],
    'activation': ['relu', 'tanh', 'logistic'],
    'solver': ['lbfgs', 'sgd', 'adam'],
    'alpha': [0.0001, 0.01],
    'max_iter': [1000],
    'tol': [1e-5]
}
print("Neural Network")
nn_params = func.gridSearch("NeuralNetwork", params, X_train, y_train)

Conclusion¶

  • With larger data, we need more time to train and test data.

    In original data, we spend 5 minutes testing, while, in pca data, we only spend 5 seconds testing.

    Surprisingly, the result in pca data performs even better.

    Although the original data can achieve this performance with the right selected parameter, the time we spend would be tremendous and not feasible for practical use.

    Therefore, it is recommended to adopt the dimensionality reduction method when we encouter big data rather than handle original data directly.
